r><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/games/2023/aug/09/the-tetris-effect-author-says-film-makers-copied-his-story-brick-by-brick" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/09/seals-practise-social-distancing-aerial-survey-of-north-sea-shows" target="_blank">Seals practise social distancing, aerial survey of North Sea shows</a></h2><div class="description"> Aerial surveys of the North Sea have revealed that seals practise social distancing. The discovery may have profound implications for the spread of disease among the marine mammals. Researchers conducting censuses of grey and harbour seals detail new evidence that the two species maintain distances between their own kind. This behaviour may “reflect an evolutionary response to viral susceptibility”</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 23:01:40 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/aug/09/seals-practise-social-distancing-aerial-survey-of-north-sea-shows" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/09/russia-ukraine-war-at-a-glance-what-we-know-on-day-532-of-the-invasion" target="_blank">Russia-Ukraine war at a glance: what we know on day 532 of the invasion</a></h2><div class="description"> The strikes on Monday evening in the downtown district of the city of Pokrovsk killed nine people and wounded more than 80 others. One of those killed was an emergency official, and most of those wounded were police officers, emergency workers and soldiers who rushed to assist residents.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 23:05:40 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/09/russia-ukraine-war-at-a-glance-what-we-know-on-day-532-of-the-invasion" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/dozens-of-secondhand-leopard-1-tanks-bought-by-eu-country-for-use-in-ukraine" target="_blank">EU country buys 49 secondhand Leopard tanks for Ukraine, arms dealer says</a></h2><div class="description"> Dozens of secondhand Leopard 1 tanks that once belonged to Belgium have been bought by a major European country for the Ukrainian army fighting Russia. It could be up to six months before they were on the battlefield in Ukraine, says the arms trader who sold them. The tanks could be in combat in six months, he says.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 21:06:59 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/dozens-of-secondhand-leopard-1-tanks-bought-by-eu-country-for-use-in-ukraine" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/ruzzki-not-welcome-the-russian-exiles-getting-a-hostile-reception-in-georgia" target="_blank">‘Ruzzki not welcome’: the Russian exiles getting a hostile reception in Georgia</a></h2><div class="description"> Thousands of Russians fled to Tbilisi after the invasion of Ukraine. But the graffiti that has sprung up across the city suggests not everyone is pleased to see them. “I went from a place I didn’t feel at home to a place that is not welcoming me” says Dima Belysh.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 04:00:03 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/ruzzki-not-welcome-the-russian-exiles-getting-a-hostile-reception-in-georgia" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/08/dollhouses-miniatures-popularity" target="_blank">‘A place where millennials can own a home’: why mini houses are having a big moment</a></h2><div class="description"> Growing interest in dollhouses suggests people find solace and joy in tiny things – especially when real homes are so pricey. The studio apartment came with modest furnishings: a small bed, a couch, books, a TV. The original dollhouse was a 1962 folding cardboard studio apartment.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:00:25 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/08/dollhouses-miniatures-popularity" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2023/aug/08/ultimate-wedding-planner-review-nothing-is-good-or-real-in-the-world-any-more" target="_blank">Ultimate Wedding Planner review – nothing is good or real in the world any more</a></h2><div class="description"> This pointless, trashy slog of a series sees wannabe organisers of nuptials badly struggle to run couples’ big days – judged by Fred Siriex. It’s so irritating it will make you need a lie down, says Tom Charity.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 21:00:37 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2023/aug/08/ultimate-wedding-planner-review-nothing-is-good-or-real-in-the-world-any-more" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/09/taiwans-metoo-movement-has-enmeshed-politicians-and-celebrities-but-a-culture-of-silence-endures" target="_blank">Taiwan’s MeToo movement has enmeshed politicians and celebrities - but a culture of silence endures</a></h2><div class="description"> Taiwan's parliament has strengthened three laws on harassment and abuse but activists say deference to elders is holding back progress. “Me and lots of my friends have faced sexual harassment, and even worse situations before,” Judy tells the Guardian in Taipei. “Finally we started to have some focus on this topic.”</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 23:24:13 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/09/taiwans-metoo-movement-has-enmeshed-politicians-and-celebrities-but-a-culture-of-silence-endures" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/08/suella-braverman-symposium-of-stupidity-delivers-blue-sky-thinking-on-asylum-seekers" target="_blank">Suella’s symposium of stupidity delivers blue-sky thinking on asylum seekers | John Crace</a></h2><div class="description"> Suella Braverman was too preoccupied to notice as she strode into the Home Office. It was the government’s August extravaganza: small boats week. The number of refugees waiting to have their asylum claims processed had risen by more than 10,000.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:37:41 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/08/suella-braverman-symposium-of-stupidity-delivers-blue-sky-thinking-on-asylum-seekers" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/08/you-will-be-missed-locals-seek-answers-about-destruction-of-crooked-house-pub" target="_blank">‘It’s gobsmacking’: locals demand answers to demolition of Crooked House pub</a></h2><div class="description"> The 260-year-old Crooked House pub in Himley, Staffordshire, caught fire after being sold. It was engulfed by flames on Saturday night before being demolished on Monday. South Staffordshire council was not given permission to demolish the pub without permission from the council.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 18:45:37 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/08/you-will-be-missed-locals-seek-answers-about-destruction-of-crooked-house-pub" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2023/aug/08/watch-out-for-the-flesh-eating-pensioner-zombieverse-netflixs-ludicrous-new-reality-horror" target="_blank">Watch out for the flesh-eating pensioner! Zombieverse, Netflix’s ludicrous new reality-horror</a></h2><div class="description"> Zombieverse is full of scares, shocked celebs and some TV trickery that is hilarious – unwittingly. British viewers coming cold to Zombieverse will have a blissful few minutes where they are not sure what they are watching. The five are stooges, contestants not on a dating show but in an immersive zombie apocalypse.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 17:00:32 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2023/aug/08/watch-out-for-the-flesh-eating-pensioner-zombieverse-netflixs-ludicrous-new-reality-horror" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/aug/08/the-death-of-the-nightclub-what-britain-will-lose-when-the-dancing-stops" target="_blank">The death of the nightclub: what Britain will lose when the dancing stops</a></h2><div class="description"> More than a third of Britain’s nightclubs have closed since June 2020. Yet they boost mental health and artistic innovation - and bring in billions for the economy. Said to have their roots in the drinking, dancing and gambling dens of mid-19th century New York.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:03:37 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/aug/08/the-death-of-the-nightclub-what-britain-will-lose-when-the-dancing-stops" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/lauren-james-made-a-stupid-mistake-but-we-need-to-have-more-compassion-moving-the-goalposts-england-womens-world-cup" target="_blank">Lauren James made a stupid mistake – but we need to have more compassion | Suzy Wrack</a></h2><div class="description"> England forward lost composure against Nigeria but people need to take into account that players are human beings too. No one will be able to beat up James more than she will be doing to herself, so why pile on? Maybe this article shouldn’t exist either; perhaps picking over the bones of the incident feels unnecessary. Maybe there are broader points to be made about what level of criticism is appropriate in the women’s game, and the men's.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:50:17 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/08/lauren-james-made-a-stupid-mistake-but-we-need-to-have-more-compassion-moving-the-goalposts-england-womens-world-cup" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'